China Guangdong Nuclear Power Group
Co. said the radiation leak at its Daya Bay plant in the
southern province of Guangdong wonâ€™t have an impact on the
environment or the health of workers, the state-owned company
said in a statement on its website today.  The No. 1 reactor, where the leak was detected on Oct. 23,
had been shut since Oct. 22 for scheduled maintenance, the
company said.   The leak was caused by a fault in a pipeline removing heat
